articles.push({
  slug: "the-content-calendar-died-heres-what-replaced-it",
  title: "The Content Calendar Died. Here's What Replaced It.",
  meta_title: "The Content Calendar Died. Here's What Replaced It.",
  excerpt: "Planning content around work you haven't done yet was always backwards. The replacement starts from the work itself.",
  content_type: "deep_dive",
  content_pillar: "growth",
  tags: ["content calendar", "content strategy", "capture first", "content automation"],
  body: 'The content calendar had a good run. For a decade, it was the organizing principle of digital marketing: plan your content in advance, assign it to dates, create it on schedule, publish on time. Brands with marketing departments used it to coordinate campaigns. Agencies used it to bill retainers. Social media managers used it to prove they were working.\n\nFor service businesses and brick-and-mortar operators, it was always the wrong model. And a better one has replaced it.\n\n## Why the Calendar Worked (for Some)\n\nContent calendars made sense for brands with marketing teams. A consumer goods company launching a product in March could plan a February awareness campaign, a March launch sequence, and an April follow-up. The content existed before it was scheduled because a team of writers, designers, and producers created it.\n\nRetail brands could plan around seasons. Fashion companies around collections. Media companies around editorial themes. The calendar worked because the content was manufactured to order. The creation infrastructure existed. The calendar just organized it.\n\n## Why It Never Worked for You\n\nYou are not a brand with a content team. You are a business owner who does real work for real clients, and the idea of planning content for next Thursday while you are elbow-deep in today project was always absurd.\n\nThe content calendar asks you to predict what you will do, create content about it in advance, and publish on schedule. But you do not control your schedule with that kind of precision. The emergency HVAC call on Tuesday, the rain delay on the construction site, the last-minute event change, the walk-in appointment that turned into your best transformation of the month -- none of that fits in a pre-planned grid.\n\nThe calendar also assumes that planning equals doing. How many times have you mapped out a month of content on a Sunday afternoon, felt productive, and then never executed a single post? The planning felt like progress. It was not. It was procrastination disguised as strategy.\n\nThis is the fundamental mismatch: content calendars were designed for businesses that manufacture content. You do not manufacture content. You manufacture kitchens, haircuts, events, dental cleanings, landscapes, meals. The content is a byproduct that the calendar model never accounted for.\n\n## The Calendar Died. Not Because It Was Bad.\n\nThe content calendar did not fail because it was a flawed concept. It failed because a better model emerged -- one that starts from reality instead of prediction.\n\nThe old model: Plan content -> Create content -> Schedule content -> Publish content.\n\nThe replacement: Do the work -> Capture the work -> Everything else is automatic.\n\nThis is capture-first marketing. The work happens. You photograph it -- a series of 5-10 photos of the project, the appointment, the event, the transformation. That capture is the trigger. Everything downstream runs without your involvement.\n\n## Capture-First: How It Works\n\nYou finish a kitchen remodel. You walk through and capture a series of photos -- the demolished space, the framing, the new cabinets, the finished room, the detail shots. You have been doing this for years anyway, for your records and your portfolio.\n\nWithin minutes of that capture, TracPost derives your brand playbook from your voice and positioning. It creates platform-native content for Instagram, TikTok, Facebook, YouTube, Pinterest, LinkedIn, X, and Google Business Profile. Not the same caption pasted eight times -- content shaped for each platform, written in the tone and format each algorithm rewards.\n\nIt produces a blog article telling the story of the project -- the challenge, the approach, the result. The article publishes to the SEO-optimized website TracPost hosts for your business. The website grows with every project. No developer. No CMS login. No quarterly update invoice.\n\nIt creates Google Business Profile posts and uploads photos to your listing. It manages review responses. When a post gains traction -- the before-and-after that resonates on Instagram, the transformation video that takes off on TikTok -- TracPost amplifies your best content with paid campaigns targeting your service area.\n\nNo calendar. No batch day. No Sunday afternoon planning session. The capture is the trigger. The work is the content.\n\n## What Changes When You Stop Planning and Start Capturing\n\nThe most immediate change is consistency. Content calendars produce bursts followed by silence -- a productive week, then three weeks of nothing. Capture-first produces content at the rhythm of your actual work. If you complete three projects a week, you produce three rounds of content a week. If you have a slow week, you have a slow content week. The rhythm matches reality instead of fighting it.\n\nThe second change is authenticity. Calendar-driven content is manufactured. Capture-first content is documented. The difference is visible to every audience on every platform. A photo of a real kitchen you just finished resonates differently than a stock image you scheduled because Thursday was "project showcase day" on your content calendar.\n\nThe third change is sustainability. Content calendars require willpower. Every month, you have to summon the discipline to plan, create, and execute. Capture-first requires a habit you already have: photographing your work. The effort is zero because the behavior already exists. The system handles everything after the shutter click.\n\n## The Replacement Is Already Here\n\nYou do not need to mourn the content calendar. You need to recognize that you never used it successfully anyway -- and that the replacement fits how you actually work.\n\nTracPost was built for capture-first. The platform does not present you with a blank calendar and ask you to fill it. It takes the photos you already capture and turns them into a complete marketing operation -- blog articles, social content across all eight platforms, a growing website, managed Google Business Profile listing, review responses, and paid amplification.\n\nThe content calendar asked you to become a marketer. Capture-first asks you to keep doing exactly what you are already doing.\n\nIf you tried the calendar approach and it did not stick, you are not undisciplined. [The calendar was the wrong tool](/blog/the-content-calendar-problem-why-scheduling-isnt-the-answer). And if you want to see what happens when one photo series becomes presence on every platform where your next customer is searching, [here is how that works](/blog/8-platforms-one-photo-how-smart-businesses-show-up-everywhere).'
});

// ─── Run updates ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

async function main() {
  // Find the TracPost site
  const sites = await sql`
    SELECT s.id FROM sites s
    WHERE s.blog_slug = 'tracpost'
    LIMIT 1
  `;

  if (sites.length === 0) {
    console.error("No site found with blog_slug = 'tracpost'");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const siteId = sites[0].id;
  console.log("Found TracPost site: " + siteId);
  console.log("Total articles to process: " + articles.length + "\n");

  let updated = 0;
  let inserted = 0;
  let errors = 0;

  for (const a of articles) {
    try {
      const existing = await sql`
        SELECT id, status FROM blog_posts WHERE site_id = ${siteId} AND slug = ${a.slug}
      `;

      const schemaJson = {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "Article",
        headline: a.title,
        description: a.excerpt,
        author: {
          "@type": "Organization",
          name: "TracPost",
          url: "https://tracpost.com",
        },
        publisher: {
          "@type": "Organization",
          name: "TracPost",
          url: "https://tracpost.com",
          logo: {
            "@type": "ImageObject",
            url: "https://tracpost.com/icon.png",
          },
        },
        datePublished: new Date().toISOString(),
        wordCount: a.body.split(/\s+/).length,
        keywords: a.tags.join(", "),
      };

      if (existing.length > 0) {
        // UPDATE -- preserve existing status
        await sql`
          UPDATE blog_posts
          SET
            body = ${a.body},
            title = ${a.title},
            meta_title = ${a.meta_title},
            excerpt = ${a.excerpt},
            meta_description = ${a.excerpt.slice(0, 155)},
            tags = ${a.tags},
            content_type = ${a.content_type},
            content_pillar = ${a.content_pillar},
            schema_json = ${JSON.stringify(schemaJson)},
            updated_at = NOW()
          WHERE site_id = ${siteId} AND slug = ${a.slug}
        `;
        console.log("UPDATED: " + a.slug + " (status preserved: " + existing[0].status + ")");
        updated++;
      } else {
        // INSERT as draft
        await sql`
          INSERT INTO blog_posts (
            site_id, slug, title, body, excerpt,
            meta_title, meta_description, schema_json,
            tags, content_type, content_pillar,
            status, published_at, source
          ) VALUES (
            ${siteId}, ${a.slug}, ${a.title}, ${a.body}, ${a.excerpt},
            ${a.meta_title}, ${a.excerpt.slice(0, 155)},
            ${JSON.stringify(schemaJson)},
            ${a.tags}, ${a.content_type}, ${a.content_pillar},
            'draft', NULL, 'generated'
          )
        `;
        console.log("INSERTED: " + a.slug);
        inserted++;
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("ERROR on " + a.slug + ": " + err.message);
      errors++;
    }
  }

  console.log("\nDone. Updated: " + updated + ", Inserted: " + inserted + ", Errors: " + errors);
}

main().catch(function(err) {
  console.error(err);
  process.exit(1);
});
